dered\n|3 days\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2018-10-04\"|2018\n|[[Meng Hongwei]]\n|data-sort-value=\"064\"|64\n|The president of [[Interpol]] visited his home country China in September 2018 and was reported missing by his wife on 4 October, after he had no contact with her or anyone else since 29 September. On 8 October, Chinese authorities confirmed that he was arrested for alleged corruption and bribery.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/politics/article/2167451/china-accuses-former-interpol-chief-meng-hongwei-taking-bribes|title=China accuses former Interpol chief of taking bribes|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=2018-10-09|language=en}}</ref>\n|Yes\n|9 Days\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2018-10-02\"|2018\n|[[Jamal Khashoggi]]\n|data-sort-value=\"059\"|59\n|The [[Saudi Arabia]]n journalist was not seen since he had an appointment at the Saudi consulate in [[Istanbul]] on 2 October 2018. Saudi state television confirmed his death on 20 October.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/19/jamal-khashoggi-dead-saudi-arabian-state-television-confirms|title=Jamal Khashoggi is dead, Saudi Arabian state television confirms|work=guardian.com|access-date=2018-10-20|language=en}}</ref> According to Turkish authorities, he was murdered by Saudi intelligence agents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2018/10/23/jamal-khashoggi-killing-investigation/1736644002/|title=Turkey says Jamal Khashoggi 'ferociously murdered' by Saudi Arabian hit squad|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-10-23|language=en}}</ref>  The murder is alleged to have been captured on listening equipment in the embassy.  \n|No / Murdered\n|Not Found\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2018-10-15\"|2018\n|[[Kidnapping of Jayme Closs|Jayme Closs]]\n|data-sort-value=\"013\"|13\n|Closs disappeared on 15 October 2018 from her home in [[Barron, Wisconsin]]. Both of her parents were shot to death and she was abducted. He pleaded guilty to two counts of [[Murder (United States law)#Degrees|first-degree intentional homicide]] and one count of [[kidnapping]]. Closs was recovered alive after she escaped on 9th January 2019. On May 24, 2019, Jake Patterson was sentenced to two consecutive life sentences in prison without the possibility of parole plus an additional 40 years. <ref>{{cite web |title=Jayme Closs located alive, suspect in custody |url=https://kstp.com/news/jayme-closs-located-alive/5206010/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111024758/https://kstp.com/news/jayme-closs-located-alive/5206010/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2019-01-11 |website=KSTP 5 |accessdate=2019-01-10|date=10 January 2019 }}</ref>\n|Yes\n|3 Months\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"2019-1-21\"| 2019\n|[[Emiliano Sala]]\n|28\n|Emiliano Sala, a footballer, disappeared two days after signing with [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] from [[FC Nantes]] in a [[2019 Piper PA-46 Malibu disappearance|suspected plane crash]] en route from [[Nantes]] to [[Cardiff]], on 21 January 2019.  <ref name=\"Insidesearch\">{{cite news |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/inside-search-emiliano-sala-what-15731596 |title=Inside the search for Emiliano Sala: What happened during three grueling days that ended in vain |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |last=Lewis |first=Anna |date=26 January 2019 |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref> [[States of Guernsey Police Service|Guernsey Police]] announced that they had called off the search for the plane or survivors.<ref name=\"Search called off\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-46992612|title=Emiliano Sala: Search for footballer and pilot called off|publisher=BBC News|date=24 January 2019}}</ref> On 3 February, it was announced that another underwater search for the aircraft had begun, using the AAIB's ''Geo Ocean III'' vessel which, together with a privately funded vessel, was conducting [[sonar]] surveys.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-47103887|title=Sala plane underwater search begins|date=3 February 2019|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> On 4 February, investigators stated that there was one body visible inside the wreckage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/one-occupant-visible-in-emiliano-sala-plane-wreckage-11627894|title='One occupant visible' in Emiliano Sala plane wreckage \u2013 investigators|website=Sky News|accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref> On 7 February, the body was formally identified as that of Sala by [[Dorset Police]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-47152773|title=Emiliano Sala search team recover body from plane wreckage|date=7 February 2019|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite news |last1=Mercer |first1=David |last2=Taylor |first2=Rebecca |title=Emiliano Sala search: Body recovered lands in Dorset |url=https://news.sky.com/story/body-recovered-from-emiliano-sala-plane-wreckage-11630221 |accessdate=7 February 2019 |work=Sky News |date=7 February 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite news |title=Body recovered from plane which crashed into English Channel confirmed as footballer Emiliano Sala |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-02-07/body-recovered-from-plane-which-crashed-into-english-channel-confirmed-as-footballer-emiliano-sala/ |accessdate=7 February 2019 |agency=ITV News |date=7 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-47166633|title=Emiliano Sala: Body identified as footballer|publisher=BBC|date=7 February 2019}}</ref>\n| No / Plane crash\n|3 \n|-\n|2019\n|David Ibbotson\n|59\n|David Ibbotson was the pilot of the plane carrying football player Emilio Sala who disappeared two days after signing with [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] from [[FC Nantes]]. The wreckage was found on 3rd February with only one body inside which was identified 3 days later as that of Sala by [[Dorset Police]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" />  The piolot is believed to have been overcome by carbon monoxide fumes.  His body has not been found.\n|No/ Accident\n|Not Found\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2019-1-21\" | 2019\n|[[Desmond Amofah]]\n|29\n|Desmond Amofah, better known by his online alias Etika, posted a YouTube video titled \"I'm sorry\" to his personal [[YouTube]] channel TR1Iceman, alluding to his suicidal thoughts as he was walking down [[New York City]] streets; in the video he admitted to having mental health issues, struggled with the attention he had been getting from streaming, and apologized for pushing people away from him.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-48756120|title=Etika: Body found in search is missing YouTuber|date=June 25, 2019|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref> He was last heard from at 8 PM that night and was reported missing to the [[New York Police Department]] (NYPD) by June 20.<ref name=\"nypost\">{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/06/21/youtube-star-etika-vanishes-after-posting-cryptic-suicidal-video/|title=YouTube star Etika vanishes after posting cryptic 'suicidal' video|last=Weissmann|first=Ruth|last2=Eustachewich|first2=Lia|date=June 21, 2019|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019}}</ref> On the evening of June 24, NYPD and emergency medical services had recovered his body near Pier 16, approximately half a mile (0.8&nbsp;km) down the [[East River]]<ref name=\"kotaku\">{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/popular-youtuber-etika-dies-at-29-1835842910|title=Popular YouTuber Etika Dies At 29|last=D'Anastasio|first=Cecilia|date=June 25, 2019|work=[[Kotaku]] |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref> and confirmed that he was deceased by the point of recovery.<ref name=\"bbc\" /> Two days later, the [[Office of Chief Medical Examiner of the City of New York|Office of Chief Medical Examiner]] determined that the cause of death was drowning, and the manner was suicide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/01/us/youtube-etika-desmond-amofah-suicide-trnd/index.html|title=YouTuber Etika died by suicide, medical examiner says|first=Alanne |last=Orjoux|website=CNN|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref>\n| No / Suicide by drowning\n|4 Days\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2019-6-30\" | 2019\n|[[Florijana Ismaili]]\n|24\n|On 29 June 2019, Switzerland national team footballer Ismaili dived into the water from a boat diving platform while on holiday at [[Lake Como]] in [[Lombardy]], but did not resurface. The next day, she was declared missing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2019/06/30/swiss-soccer-player-florijana-ismaili-missing-after-swimming-accident/|title=Swiss soccer player Florijana Ismaili missing after swimming accident|work=New York Post|date=30 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ocnal.com/2019/06/swiss-footballer-floriana-ismaili.html | title = Swiss footballer Floriana Ismaili disappeared while swimming in Como Lake | publisher = Oculus News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48821383|title=Florijana Ismaili: Swiss player declared missing after swimming accident|date=June 30, 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Local authorities conducted an investigation, including using [[remotely operated underwater vehicle]]s (ROV). On 2 July, Ismaili's body was found at the bottom of Lake Como at a depth of 204 metres (669 feet).<ref>{{cite news |date=2 July 2019 |title=Switzerland player Ismaili confirmed dead in swim accident |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2019/07/02/switzerland-player-ismaili-confirmed-dead-in-swim-accident/39648609/ |work=[[USA Today]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=2 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48851151|title=Florijana Ismaili: Tributes paid after body of missing Swiss player is found|date=July 3, 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> An [[autopsy]] revealed that the cause of death was from \"an acute episode of asphyxia.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/florijana-ismaili_swiss-national-football-player-feared-drowned-in-lake-como/45066692|title=Swiss national football player died from asphyxia|publisher=swissinfo.ch|date=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n| No / Drowning\n|3 Days\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Biography|History|Lists}}\n\n* [[Forced disappearance]]\n* [[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n* [[List of kidnappings]]\n* [[List of murder convictions without a body]]\n* [[List of people who disappeared mysteriously: post-1970]]\n* [[List of people who disappeared mysteriously: pre-1970]]\n* [[List of unidentified murder victims in the United States]]\n* [[List of unsolved deaths]]\n* [[List of unsolved murders]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of people by cause of death|Disappeared]]\n[[Category:Lists of unexplained disappearances|People]]\n[[Category:Missing people| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{For|other lists of disappeared persons|Lists of people who disappeared}}\n{{dynamic list}}\n\nThis is a '''list of solved missing persons cases''' of people who went missing in unknown locations or unknown circumstances that were eventually explained by their reappearance or the recovery of their bodies, or the conviction of the perpetrator(s) responsible for their disappearances.\n\n<!--By consensus, entries must be those of people or disappearances that are notable because an article about them already exists. Do not add an entry if you cannot link to such an article.-->\n<!--When adding ages to these tables please note:\n\n* If any person went missing below the age of 10 (i.e. single digits), please use data-sort-value for those persons on the date value to ensure that it is kept at the top. e.g. for an age of 8, use data-sort-value=\"008\"\n* If any person went missing below the age of 1 (i.e. they were X weeks/months old), please use data-sort-value for those persons on the date value to ensure that it is kept at the top. e.g. for an age of 9 weeks, work what proportion of that age was in a year:\n      * Use the formula for age in months (assuming equal length of months):\n            (age in months)/12\n      * Use the formula for age in weeks (assuming 4 weeks in a month):\n            (age in weeks)/(12*4)\n      * Use the formula for age in days (assuming 4 weeks in a month and 7 days per week):\n            (age in days)/(12*4*7)\n\n* If any person in the table was missing above the age of 100, please ensure that ALL of the other dates use data-sort-value. e.g. for an age of 50 use data-sort-value=\"050\"\n\nThis ensures that ages are in the right order\n-->\n{{horizontal TOC|nonum=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n\n==Before 1900==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"|Date\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Person(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Age \n! class=\"unsortable\"|Circumstances\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Found alive / cause of death\n! data-sort-type=\"value\"|Time spent missing or unconfirmed\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1553-05-10\"|1553\n|[[Hugh Willoughby|Sir Hugh Willoughby]]\n|\n|Sir Hugh Willoughby, an English explorer, set sail from London on 10 May 1553 to search for a sea route right around the north of Europe and Asia to China. His second-in-command was [[Richard Chancellor]] of Bristol. Off the coast of Norway the two men were separated by a storm. Willoughby's ship ended up stuck in ice off [[S\u00e1pmi|Lapland]] and he and all of his crew died. Their frozen bodies were found the following year.<!-- <ref>{{cite book|last1=Fowke|first1=Bob|title=What They Don't Tell You About The Tudors|date=2001|publisher=[[Hodder Children's Books]] | location=London|isbn=978-0-340-78808-0 | page=88}}</ref> appears incorrect - Wikipedia article shows only 1 year-->\n|No\n|data-sort-value=\"0365\"|1 year\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1660-08-16\"|1660\n|[[The Campden Wonder|William Harrison]]\n|70\n|William Harrison disappeared on 16 August 1660 from the town of [[Chipping Campden]], Gloucestershire and was thought to have been murdered. He resurfaced two years later and said that he had been kidnapped.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-nottinghamshire-37577247|title=Lost girl who helped change the law|last=Watson|first=Greig|date=2017|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-12-21|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210151655/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-nottinghamshire-37577247|archive-date=10 December 2017}}</ref>\n|Yes\n|data-sort-value=\"0730\"|2 years\n|-\n|1892\n|[[Gottlieb Fluhmann]] \n|c. 55\n|The [[Colorado]] rancher was last seen in 1892 before he disappeared under strange and largely unknown circumstances. His body was found in 1944, but the cause of death could not be determined.\n|No / Unknown\n|data-sort-value=\"18980\"|52 years\n|}\n\n==1900\u20131949==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"|Date\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Person(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Age \n! class=\"unsortable\"|Circumstances\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Found alive / cause of death\n! data-sort-type=\"value\"|Time spent missing or unconfirmed\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1910-08-20\"|1910\n|[[Crime of Cuenca|Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Grimaldos L\u00f3pez]]\n|28\n|Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Grimaldos L\u00f3pez, a [[shepherd]] from [[Tresjuncos]], Spain, went missing on 20 August 1910. Two men were convicted of his killing after confessing under torture. Grimaldos resurfaced in 1926.<ref>{{Cite web |first=\u00c1ngel Luis L\u00f3pez |last=Villaverde |url=http://www.uclm.es/ceclm/publicaciones/rp_clm03.htm |title=El crimen de Cuenca en treinta art\u00edculos: antolog\u00eda period\u00edstica del error judicial |trans-title=The crime of Cuenca in thirty articles: journalistic anthology of judicial error |publisher=[[University of Castilla\u2013La Mancha|Universidad de Castilla\u2013La Mancha]] |date=2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222162608/https://previa.uclm.es/ceclm/publicaciones/rp_clm03.htm |archive-date=22 December 2017 |access-date=30 March 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|Yes\n|data-sort-value=\"5,613\"|16 years\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1911-04-08\"|1911\n|[[Elsie Paroubek]]\n|data-sort-value=\"005\"|5\n|Elsie Paroubek was a [[Czech American]] girl who disappeared in [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]], on 8 April 1911. On 9 May 1911, employees of the [[Lockport, Illinois|Lockport]] power plant near [[Joliet, Illinois|Joliet]], thirty-five miles outside of Chicago, saw a body floating in the [[Chicago Sanitary and Ship Canal]], which was identified as hers.<ref>\"The \"gypsies\" had left Round Lake when we reached there and we traced them to Volo, Illinois, and then to McHenry, where we found the band,\" said Det. Sheehan. \"They had a girl about 5-years old with them, but she was not the missing child. Instead of having blond hair as reported by a number of persons, she had deep black hair and the dark complexion of the gypsies. She was the daughter of one of the gypsies and there was no other girl in the band.\" \"Return: Quest for Girl in Vain\". ''Chicago Daily News'', 15 April 1911, p. 2.</ref>\n|No / Murdered\n|data-sort-value=\"0031\"|31 days\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1913-02-09\"|1913\n|Captain [[Robert Falcon Scott]] & his group\n|\n|Captain Scott and his party of explorers were found 13 months after their disappearance on their [[South Pole]] expedition.\n|No / [[Hypothermia]] & starvation\n|data-sort-value=\"0396\"|13 months\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1926-12\"|1926\n|[[Agatha Christie]]\n|36\n|Agatha Christie, a famous British crime writer, [[Agatha_Christie#Disappearance:_1926|famously disappeared]] in December 1926, after her husband asked for a divorce. She was located alive 10 days later in a [[Yorkshire]] health spa, and always refused to give an explanation.<ref>{{Cite news |title=MRS. CHRISTIE FOUND IN A YORKSHIRE SPA; Missing Novelist, Under an Assumed Name, Was Staying at a Hotel There. CLUE A NEWSPAPER PICTURE Mystery Writer Is Victim of Loss of Memory, Her Husband Declares. MRS. CHRISTIE FOUND IN A YORKSHIRE SPA |newspaper=New York Times |date=15 December 1926 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1926/12/15/archives/mrs-christie-found-in-a-yorkshire-spa-missing-novelist-under-an.html |accessdate=16 September 2009}}</ref>\n|Yes\n|data-sort-value=\"0010\"|10 days\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1928-01-01\"|1928  \n|[[Walter Collins]] \n|9\n|Collins disappeared from his home in [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]], in 1928. He was later determined to have been murdered by [[Gordon Stewart Northcott]] in what was known as the [[Wineville Chicken Coop Murders]]. His disappearance and the attempt by the Los Angeles police department to convince his mother that a different boy was her son formed the basis of the 2008 film ''[[Changeling (film)|Changeling]]''.<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/465341642.html?dids=465341642:465341642&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&date=Apr+04%2C+1928pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=New+Kidnaping+Clew+Furnished+in+Hunt+for+Missing+Collins+Boy New Kidnaping Clew Furnished in Hunt for Missing Collins Boy] ''Los Angeles Times'' 4 April 1928.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Foundas |first=Scott |title=Clint Eastwood: The Set Whisperer \u2013 Shooting quietly on the Changeling set |newspaper=[[LA Weekly]] |date=December 19, 2007 |url=http://www.laweekly.com/film+tv/film/clint-eastwood-the-set-whisperer/17910/ |access-date=December 29, 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20071223025728/http://www.laweekly.com/film+tv/film/clint-eastwood-the-set-whisperer/17910/ |archive-date=December 23, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Susan |author-link=Susan King (journalist) |title=Changeling actor reveres his boss: Clint Eastwood |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=September 7, 2008 |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2008/sep/07/entertainment/ca-changeling7 |access-date=September 5, 2008}}</ref>\n|No / Murdered\n|data-sort-value=\"730\"|2 years<!-- ? estimate -->\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1932-03-01\"|1932\n|[[Lindbergh kidnapping|Charles Augustus Lindbergh Jr.]]\n|1\n|On March 1, 1932, Charles Augustus Lindbergh Jr., 20-month-old son of aviator [[Charles Lindbergh]] and [[Anne Morrow Lindbergh]], was abducted from the crib in the upper floor of his home in [[Highfields (Amwell and Hopewell, New Jersey)|Highfields]] in [[East Amwell, New Jersey|East Amwell]], [[New Jersey]], [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite news | first=Barbara |last=Gill |title=Lindbergh kidnapping rocked the world 50 years ago |work=[[The Hunterdon County Democrat]]  |year=1981 |accessdate=December 30, 2008 |quote=So while the world's attention was focused on Hopewell, from which the first press dispatches emanated about the kidnapping, the Democrat made sure its readers knew that the new home of Col. Charles A. Lindbergh and Anne Morrow Lindbergh was in East Amwell Township, Hunterdon County. |url=http://www.nj.com/lindbergh/hunterdon/index.ssf?/lindbergh/stories/demcovr.html |df=dmy-all}}</ref> On May 12, the child's corpse was discovered by a truck driver by the side of a nearby road.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Aiuto |first=Russell |title=The Theft of the Eaglet |work=The Lindbergh Kidnapping |publisher=TruTv |url=http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/notorious_murders/famous/lindbergh/index_1.html |accessdate=June 24, 2009 |df=dmy-all |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601183654/http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/notorious_murders/famous/lindbergh/index_1.html |archive-date=1 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Lindbergh Kidnapping Index |url=http://www.charleslindbergh.com/kidnap/ |accessdate=October 16, 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|No / Murder\n|data-sort-value=\"072\"|72 days\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"1934-08-27\"|1934\n|[[Linda Agostini]]\n|28\n|Linda Agostini was a woman who emigrated from [[South London|South East London]] to Australia, and disappeared from Melbourne on 27 Au