side the search for Emiliano Sala: What happened during three grueling days that ended in vain |work=WalesOnline |publisher=Media Wales |last=Lewis |first=Anna |date=26 January 2019 |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref> [[States of Guernsey Police Service|Guernsey Police]] announced that they had called off the search for the plane or survivors.<ref name=\"Search called off\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-46992612|title=Emiliano Sala: Search for footballer and pilot called off|publisher=BBC News|date=24 January 2019}}</ref> On 3 February, it was announced that another underwater search for the aircraft had begun, using the AAIB's ''Geo Ocean III'' vessel which, together with a privately funded vessel, was conducting [[sonar]] surveys.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-47103887|title=Sala plane underwater search begins|date=3 February 2019|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> On 4 February, investigators stated that there was one body visible inside the wreckage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/one-occupant-visible-in-emiliano-sala-plane-wreckage-11627894|title='One occupant visible' in Emiliano Sala plane wreckage \u2013 investigators|website=Sky News|accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref> On 7 February, the body was formally identified as that of Sala by [[Dorset Police]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-47152773|title=Emiliano Sala search team recover body from plane wreckage|date=7 February 2019|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite news |last1=Mercer |first1=David |last2=Taylor |first2=Rebecca |title=Emiliano Sala search: Body recovered lands in Dorset |url=https://news.sky.com/story/body-recovered-from-emiliano-sala-plane-wreckage-11630221 |accessdate=7 February 2019 |work=Sky News |date=7 February 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite news |title=Body recovered from plane which crashed into English Channel confirmed as footballer Emiliano Sala |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-02-07/body-recovered-from-plane-which-crashed-into-english-channel-confirmed-as-footballer-emiliano-sala/ |accessdate=7 February 2019 |agency=ITV News |date=7 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-47166633|title=Emiliano Sala: Body identified as footballer|publisher=BBC|date=7 February 2019}}</ref>\n| No / Plane crash\n|3 \n|-\n|2019\n|David Ibbotson\n|59\n|David Ibbotson was the pilot of the plane carrying football player Emilio Sala who disappeared two days after signing with [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] from [[FC Nantes]]. The wreckage was found on 3rd February with only one body inside which was identified 3 days later as that of Sala by [[Dorset Police]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" />  The piolot is believed to have been overcome by carbon monoxide fumes.  His body has not been found.\n|No/ Accident\n|Not Found\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2019-1-21\" | 2019\n|[[Desmond Amofah]]\n|29\n|Desmond Amofah, better known by his online alias Etika, posted a YouTube video titled \"I'm sorry\" to his personal [[YouTube]] channel TR1Iceman, alluding to his suicidal thoughts as he was walking down [[New York City]] streets; in the video he admitted to having mental health issues, struggled with the attention he had been getting from streaming, and apologized for pushing people away from him.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-48756120|title=Etika: Body found in search is missing YouTuber|date=June 25, 2019|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref> He was last heard from at 8 PM that night and was reported missing to the [[New York Police Department]] (NYPD) by June 20.<ref name=\"nypost\">{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/06/21/youtube-star-etika-vanishes-after-posting-cryptic-suicidal-video/|title=YouTube star Etika vanishes after posting cryptic 'suicidal' video|last=Weissmann|first=Ruth|last2=Eustachewich|first2=Lia|date=June 21, 2019|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=June 25, 2019}}</ref> On the evening of June 24, NYPD and emergency medical services had recovered his body near Pier 16, approximately half a mile (0.8&nbsp;km) down the [[East River]]<ref name=\"kotaku\">{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/popular-youtuber-etika-dies-at-29-1835842910|title=Popular YouTuber Etika Dies At 29|last=D'Anastasio|first=Cecilia|date=June 25, 2019|work=[[Kotaku]] |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref> and confirmed that he was deceased by the point of recovery.<ref name=\"bbc\" /> Two days later, the [[Office of Chief Medical Examiner of the City of New York|Office of Chief Medical Examiner]] determined that the cause of death was drowning, and the manner was suicide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/01/us/youtube-etika-desmond-amofah-suicide-trnd/index.html|title=YouTuber Etika died by suicide, medical examiner says|first=Alanne |last=Orjoux|website=CNN|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref>\n| No / Suicide by drowning\n|4 Days\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2019-6-30\" | 2019\n|[[Florijana Ismaili]]\n|24\n|On 29 June 2019, Switzerland national team footballer Ismaili dived into the water from a boat diving platform while on holiday at [[Lake Como]] in [[Lombardy]], but did not resurface. The next day, she was declared missing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2019/06/30/swiss-soccer-player-florijana-ismaili-missing-after-swimming-accident/|title=Swiss soccer player Florijana Ismaili missing after swimming accident|work=New York Post|date=30 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ocnal.com/2019/06/swiss-footballer-floriana-ismaili.html | title = Swiss footballer Floriana Ismaili disappeared while swimming in Como Lake | publisher = Oculus News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48821383|title=Florijana Ismaili: Swiss player declared missing after swimming accident|date=June 30, 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Local authorities conducted an investigation, including using [[remotely operated underwater vehicle]]s (ROV). On 2 July, Ismaili's body was found at the bottom of Lake Como at a depth of 204 metres (669 feet).<ref>{{cite news |date=2 July 2019 |title=Switzerland player Ismaili confirmed dead in swim accident |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2019/07/02/switzerland-player-ismaili-confirmed-dead-in-swim-accident/39648609/ |work=[[USA Today]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=2 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48851151|title=Florijana Ismaili: Tributes paid after body of missing Swiss player is found|date=July 3, 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> An [[autopsy]] revealed that the cause of death was from \"an acute episode of asphyxia.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/florijana-ismaili_swiss-national-football-player-feared-drowned-in-lake-como/45066692|title=Swiss national football player died from asphyxia|publisher=swissinfo.ch|date=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n| No / Drowning\n|3 Days\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Biography|History|Lists}}\n\n* [[Forced disappearance]]\n* [[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n* [[List of kidnappings]]\n* [[List of murder convictions without a body]]\n* [[List of people who disappeared mysteriously: post-1970]]\n* [[List of people who disappeared mysteriously: pre-1970]]\n* [[List of unidentified murder victims in the United States]]\n* [[List of unsolved deaths]]\n* [[List of unsolved murders]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of people by cause of death|Disappeared]]\n[[Category:Lists of unexplained disappearances|People]]\n[[Category:Missing people| ]]\n", "name_user": "Dougmcdonell", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2000s:correct typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_solved_missing_persons_cases"}
{"title_page": "Disney Princess", "text_new": "{{About|the Disney Princess media franchise||List of Disney animated universe characters}}\n{{short description|Media franchise of The Walt Disney Company}}\n{{Infobox media franchise\n|title       = Disney Princess\n|image       = File:DisneyPrincessLineup2013.jpg\n|imagesize   = 250px\n|caption     = The 2013 line-up of the Disney Princess franchise. From left to right: [[Mulan (Disney character)|Mulan]], [[Snow White (Disney character)|Snow White]], [[Tiana (Disney)|Tiana]], [[Cinderella (Disney character)|Cinderella]], [[Belle (Beauty and the Beast)|Belle]], [[Merida (Brave)|Merida]], [[Rapunzel (Tangled)|Rapunzel]], [[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]], [[Aurora (Disney)|Aurora]], [[Jasmine (Disney character)|Jasmine]], and [[Pocahontas (character)|Pocahontas]]\n|creator     = [[Andy Mooney]]\n|origin      = Animated films <br /> Animated series\n|books       = ''[[#Literature|Disney Princess Chapter Books]]''<br /> ''[[#Literature|A Jewel Story]]''\n|novels      = May 7, 2005 \u2013 present\n|comics      = {{ubl|''[[Kilala Princess]]''|''Disney Princesses'' series|Disney Princess Comics}}\n|magazines   = ''Disney Princess''\n|films       = ''[[Disney Princess Enchanted Tales: Follow Your Dreams|Enchanted Tales: Follow Your Dreams]]''\n|atv         = {{unbulleted list|''[[Toon Disney#Blocks|The Princess Power Hour]]'' {{small|(block)}}|''[[Sofia the First]]''|''[[Whisker Haven|Whisker Haven Tales with the Palace Pets]]''}}\n|vgs         =\n*''[[Disney Princess: Enchanted Journey|Enchanted Journey]]'' \n*''[[Disney Princess: My Fairytale Adventure|Fairytale Adventure]]''\n|music       =\n*''[[Disney's Princess Favorites]]''\n*''[[Disney Princess: The Ultimate Song Collection]]''\n*''[[Disney Princess Tea Party]]''\n*''[[Ultimate Disney Princess]]''\n|toys        = {{ubl|Dolls|Palace Pets|Comics line figures}}\n|otherlabel1 = Extension\n|otherdata1  = Palace Pets<ref name=ppets/>\n|otherlabel2 = Clothing\n|otherdata2  = [[Disney's Fairy Tale Weddings & Honeymoons#Dress line|Disney Fairy Tale Weddings collection]]\n}}\n'''''Disney Princess''''', also called the '''''Princess Line''''',<ref name=\"lat1\"/> is a [[media franchise]] and [[toy-line]] owned by [[The Walt Disney Company]]. Created in the 90s, the franchise features a line-up of [[List of Disney characters by film|fictional female protagonists]] who have appeared in various [[Disney animated features canon|Disney franchises]].\n\nThe franchise does not include all princess characters from the whole of Disney-owned media, but rather refers to select specific characters from the company's animated films and series. The 12 characters considered part of the franchise are [[Snow White (Disney character)|Snow White]], [[Cinderella (Disney character)|Cinderella]], [[Aurora (Disney)|Aurora]], [[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]], [[Belle (Beauty and the Beast)|Belle]], [[Jasmine (Disney character)|Jasmine]], [[Pocahontas (character)|Pocahontas]], [[Mulan (Disney character)|Mulan]], [[Tiana (Disney)|Tiana]], [[Rapunzel (Tangled)|Rapunzel]], [[Merida (Brave)|Merida]], and [[Moana (character)|Moana]].\n\nThe franchise has released dolls, sing-along videos, apparel, beauty products, home decor, toys and a variety of other products featuring some of the Disney Princesses.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fisher-Price Disney Princess Review|url=http://www.thehottoys.com/2013/03/fisher-price-disney-princess-review/|work=thehottoys.com|accessdate=26 August 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002114103/http://www.thehottoys.com/2013/03/fisher-price-disney-princess-review/|archivedate=October 2, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Licensees for the franchise include [[Glidden (paints)|Glidden]] (wall paint), [[Stride Rite]] (sparkly shoes), [[Hasbro]] (games and dolls), and [[Fisher-Price]] (plastic figurines).<ref name=bbw/>\n{{TOC limit|limit=3}}\n\n==History==\n===1990s===\nIn 1994 the toy company [[Mattel]] started selling products that featured all the most popular Disney Princesses together.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Block|first1=Tara|title='90s Toys You Probably Have Stashed Away That Are Worth a LOT of Money Now|url=https://www.popsugar.co.uk/love/photo-gallery/45094984/image/45094800/Disney-Perfume-Princesses |work=PopSugar}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Disney Princesses, licensed to Mattel |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702020122/http://www.whos-that-doll.com/disney_princess_dolls.html |website=Who's That Doll?}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=45 Awesome Toys Every \u201990s Girl Wanted For Christmas |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/briangalindo/awesome-toys-every-9s-girl-wanted-for-christmas |website=BuzzFeed}}</ref> This was the first time the characters were marketed in a separate franchise to their original films.\n\nOn May 4, 1995, Walt Disney Home Video launched  the ''Disney Princess Collection'', a series of VHSs and laser discs containing episodes from [[Aladdin (TV series)|Aladdin]], [[The Little Mermaid (TV series)|The Little Mermaid]] and two Beauty and the Beast specials.<ref>{{cite web |title=Disney Princess Collection |url=https://www.lddb.com/laserdisc/06345/4143-AS/Princess-Collection:-Jasmine%27s-Enchanted-Tales:-The-Greatest-Treasure/Jasmine%27s-Wish |website=LaserDisc Database}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, 1996, [[Walt Disney Records]] released the first Princess soundtrack album.<ref>{{cite web |title=Disney's Princess Collection: The Music Of Hopes, Dreams And Happy Endings |url=https://www.discogs.com/it/Various-Disneys-Princess-Collection-The-Music-Of-Hopes-Dreams-And-Happy-Endings/release/7537334 |website=Discogs}}</ref> The album went on to peak at #4 on [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'s Top Kid Audio chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chart History |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/various-artists/chart-history/KID/song/192431 |website=Billboard}}</ref>\n\nThe first issue of the Disney Princess Magazine was published on June 24, 1998 in the United Kingdom,<ref>{{cite news |title=Disney Princess Magazine celebrates increase in sales as it turns 21 |url=https://www.egmont.co.uk/blog/disney-princess-magazine-turns-21/ |publisher=[[Egmont Group]] |date=January 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Disney's Princess |url=https://www.wolfstad.com/dcw/united-kingdom/disneys-princess/ |website=Disney Comics Worldwide}}</ref> and in September 1999 in Denmark.<ref>{{cite web |title=Disney Prinsesser Hjemmet |url=https://www.comics.org/series/78661/covers/ |website=[[Grand Comics Database]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999 [[Disney Consumer Products]] officially launched the Princess brand at the [[Disney Store]].<ref name=\"disneyconsumerproducts\">{{cite web|title=Disney Consumer Products|publisher=The Walt Disney Company|url=https://licensing.disney.com/Login/displayContent.do?layout=fftDetail&fftId=disney_princess|date=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060323155139/https://licensing.disney.com/Login/displayContent.do?layout=fftDetail&fftId=disney_princess|archivedate=March 23, 2006}}</ref>\n\nWalt's nephew, [[Roy E. Disney]], objected to the creation of the brand, as the company has long \"avoided mingling characters from its classic fairy tales in other narratives, worrying that it would weaken the individual mythologies\".<ref name=\"lat1\">{{cite news|last1=Barnes|first1=Brooks|title=The Line Between Homage and Parody|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/25/business/media/25steal.html?_r=0|accessdate=August 15, 2016|work=Los Angeles Times|date=November 25, 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415065157/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/25/business/media/25steal.html?_r=0|archivedate=April 15, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2000s===\nFormer [[Nike, Inc.]] executive [[Andy Mooney]] was appointed president of [[The Walt Disney Company]]'s [[Disney Consumer Products]] division in December 1999, taking the place of [[Anne Osberg]].<ref name=mooneyhollywoodreporter>{{cite web|last=Bond|first=Paul|title=Disney's Head of Consumer Products Resigns|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disneys-head-consumer-products-resigns-231704|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=12 April 2013|date=September 6, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409175834/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disneys-head-consumer-products-resigns-231704|archivedate=April 9, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Disney Hires Away Nike Marketer For Consumer-Products Division |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB945128440385048945 |publisher=The Wall Street Journal |date=December 14, 1999}}</ref>\n\nWhile attending his first [[Disney on Ice]] show in 2000, Mooney noticed that several young girls attending the show were dressed in princess attire\u2014though not authentic Disney merchandise.<ref name=\"what'swrongwithcinderella\">{{cite news|last=Orenstein|first=Peggy|title=What's Wrong With Cinderella?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/24/magazine/24princess.t.html?pagewanted=2&_r=0&ei=5088&en=8e5a1ac1332a802c&ex=1324616400&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|accessdate=12 April 2013|date=December 24, 2006|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515211326/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/24/magazine/24princess.t.html?pagewanted=2&_r=0&ei=5088&en=8e5a1ac1332a802c&ex=1324616400&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss|archivedate=May 15, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"They were generic princess products they\u2019d appended to a Halloween costume,\" Mooney told ''[[The New York Times]]''. Concerned by this, Mooney addressed the company the following morning \"O.K., let's establish standards and a color palette and talk to licensees and get as much product out there as we possibly can\".<ref name=\"what'swrongwithcinderella\"/>\n\nThe 2000s line-up consisted of princesses [[Snow White (Disney character)|Snow White]], [[Cinderella (Disney character)|Cinderella]], [[Aurora (Disney)|Aurora]], [[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]], [[Belle (Beauty and the Beast)|Belle]], [[Princess Jasmine|Jasmine]], [[Pocahontas (character)|Pocahontas]], [[Mulan (Disney character)|Mulan]] and [[Tinker Bell]]. Tinker Bell was soon removed from the line-up; she would go on to headline the sister franchise ''[[Disney Fairies]]''.  Mooney decided that, when featured on marketing advertisements such as posters, the princesses should never make eye contact with each other in an attempt to keep their individual \"mythologies\" intact. \"[Each] stares off in a slightly different direction as if unaware of the others' presence.\"<ref name=\"what'swrongwithcinderella\"/>\n\nBy 2001, Disney Consumer Products (DCP) had generated about 300 million dollars, but by 2012, the division had increased revenue to 3 billion dollars, making it the top seller of consumer entertainment products globally.<ref>{{cite web|last1=NG|first1=Vincent|title=How Disney Princesses Became a Multibillion Dollar Brand|url=http://www.mcngmarketing.com/how-disney-princesses-became-a-multi-billion-dollar-brand/#.VzjXKKODGkq|website=MCNG Marketing|publisher=Word Press|accessdate=15 May 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405052008/http://www.mcngmarketing.com/how-disney-princesses-became-a-multi-billion-dollar-brand/#.VzjXKKODGkq|archivedate=April 5, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> DCP issued princess product licenses to Hasbro for games, Mattel for dolls, and Fisher-Price for plastic figurines in 2000, allowing the franchise to meet the $1 billion mark in revenue in three years.<ref name=bbw>{{cite news |last1=Suddath |first1=Claire |title=The $500 Million Battle Over Disney's Princesses |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2015-disney-princess-hasbro/ |accessdate=February 18, 2016 |work=Bloomberg Businessweek |date=December 17, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170208181738/https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2015-disney-princess-hasbro/ |archivedate=February 8, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Expansions===\nTiana became the first additional character to the Princess franchise officially on March 14, 2010, taking Tinker Bell's short-lived place as the ninth member. Her \"coronation\" took place at the [[Lotte New York Palace Hotel|New York Palace]].<ref name=cbs0>{{cite news|title=What you don't know about Disney princesses: Demoted princess|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/what-you-dont-know-about-disney-princesses/5/|accessdate=August 14, 2016|work=CBS News|pages=5, 6|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821190047/http://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/what-you-dont-know-about-disney-princesses/17/|archivedate=August 21, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"tianacoronation\">\n{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Princess Tiana Officially Joins the Disney Princess Royal Court at Star-Studded Crowning Event in New York City  |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20100314005046/en/Princess-Tiana-Officially-Joins-Disney-Princess-Royal |url-status= |format= |type=Press release |language= |location= |publisher=Disney Consumer Products  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214161040/http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20100314005046/en/Princess-Tiana-Officially-Joins-Disney-Princess-Royal |archive-date=December 14, 2014  |access-date=December 15, 2014 |via=Business Wire |quote= |ref= }}</ref> Tinker Bell was already heading up another franchise started in 2005, [[Disney Fairies]].<ref name=cbs0/> Rapunzel was crowned and inducted into the Disney Princess franchise as the tenth member on October 2, 2011, at [[Kensington Palace]] in [[London, England]].<ref name=rapunzelcoronation>{{cite news|title=Disney Throws a Party in London for Rapunzel|url=http://www.foxnews.com/travel/2011/09/29/disney-throws-party-in-london-for-rapunzel/|accessdate=March 6, 2014|newspaper=Fox News|date=September 29, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514160553/http://www.foxnews.com/travel/2011/09/29/disney-throws-party-in-london-for-rapunzel/|archivedate=May 14, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On May 11, 2013, Disney added the first [[Pixar]] character Merida as the 11th Princess to the franchise in a coronation ceremony in front of Cinderella Castle at [[Magic Kingdom]] in [[Walt Disney World]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Merida becomes Disney's 11th Princess in a ceremony at the Magic Kingdom|url=http://attractionsmagazine.com/merida-becomes-disneys-11th-princess-in-a-ceremony-at-the-magic-kingdom-video-and-photos/|accessdate=March 7, 2014|newspaper=Orlando Attractions Magazine|date=May 11, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307095134/http://attractionsmagazine.com/merida-becomes-disneys-11th-princess-in-a-ceremony-at-the-magic-kingdom-video-and-photos/|archivedate=March 7, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  By March 21, 2019, [[Moana (character)|Moana]] was added to the line-up without having a coronation ceremony, but rather being included in future merchandise.<ref name=\"atmag\">{{cite news |last1=Tuttle |first1=Brittani |title=What makes a princess a Disney Princess? |url=https://attractionsmagazine.com/disney-princess-fox-lineup/ |accessdate=October 29, 2019 |work=Attractions Magazine |date=March 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA line of [[Disney's Fairy Tale Weddings & Honeymoons#Dress line|Disney Fairy Tale Wedding]] gowns were designed by Kirstie Kelly, based on the Princesses and available in January 2008.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sotonoff |first1=Jamie |title=New Disney dresses let brides be princesses -- Daily Herald |url=http://prev.dailyherald.com/story/?id=111196 |accessdate=November 11, 2019 |work=Daily Herald |publisher=Paddock Publications, Inc. |date=January 11, 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Disney Princesses at Merida's coronation.jpg|thumb|250px|The Disney Princesses gathered at the coronation of Merida in 2013]]\nWith the [[Target Corporation]] as its marketing partner, Disney held the first National Princess Week the week of April 22, 2012. During the week, there was the release of ''[[The Princess Diaries (film)|The Princess Diaries]]'' Blu-ray and ''The Very Fairy Princess'' book.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Judkis|first1=Maura|title=National Princess Week: 'Inner sparkle,' at a price|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/arts-post/post/national-princess-week-inner-sparkle-at-a-price/2012/04/26/gIQAV3UgjT_blog.html|accessdate=October 27, 2017|work=The Washington Post|date=April 26, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171106132752/https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/arts-post/post/national-princess-week-inner-sparkle-at-a-price/2012/04/26/gIQAV3UgjT_blog.html|archivedate=November 6, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Harrod, already have a [[Disney Store#Disney at Harrods|Disney stores]] within, followed with their Christmas theme being Disney Princesses by having an Oscar de la Renta designed dress for the Princess on display.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Mark J.|last1=Miller|title=It's Beginning to Look a Lot Like Disney at Harrods|url=http://brandchannel.com/2012/06/11/its-beginning-to-look-a-lot-like-disney-at-harrods/|accessdate=27 October 2017|work=Brandchannel|date=11 June 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027232251/http://brandchannel.com/2012/06/11/its-beginning-to-look-a-lot-like-disney-at-harrods/|archivedate=October 27, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In August, the dress was on display at [[D23 (Disney)|D23 Expo]] before being auctioned on November 13 to benefit [[Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lidbury|first1=Olivia|title=Harrods' Disney-inspired dresses go up for auction - Telegraph|url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG10240354/Harrods-Disney-inspired-dresses-go-up-for-auction.html|work=Telegraph|date=14 August 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219064938/http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG10240354/Harrods-Disney-inspired-dresses-go-up-for-auction.html|archivedate=December 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\t \n[[Mattel]] added a Barbie princess-themed line in late-2010, then the fairy tale based ''[[Ever After High]]'' in 2013.With these competing lines and an expiration of the brand license at the end of 2015, Disney offered [[Hasbro]] a chance to gain the license given their work on Star Wars, which led to a ''[[Descendants (2015 film)|Descendants]]'' license. DCP was also attempting to evolve the brand by marketing them less as damsels and more as heroines. In September 2014, Disney announced that Hasbro would be the licensed doll maker for the Disney Princess line starting on January 1, 2016.<ref name=bbw/>\n\nThe June 2013 release of the Disney Princess Palace Pets app from Disney Publishing, led DCP to turn Palace Pets into a Disney Princess franchise extension, which led to the release of The Palace Pets toy line in August from licensee Blip Toys. The line was also selected by TimetoPlayMag.com for its Most Wanted List Holiday 2013.<ref name=ppets>{{cite news|last1=Goldman Getzler|first1=Wendy|title=Disney nurtures Palace Pet project, tablet usage|url=http://kidscreen.com/2013/10/02/disney-nurtures-palace-pet-project-tablet-usage/|accessdate=July 1, 2014|work=Kidscreen/iKids|publisher=Brunico Communications Ltd|date=October 2, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714145943/http://kidscreen.com/2013/10/02/disney-nurtures-palace-pet-project-tablet-usage/|archivedate=July 14, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2015 Disney Publishing released animated shorts series ''[[Whisker Haven Tales with the Palace Pets]]''. The shorts journey to a magical world of Whisker Haven, a secret realm located in a fairy-tale space between the Disney Princess kingdoms.<ref>{{Cite web|title = 'Tradition Meets Innovation' at Disney Consumer Products Showcase at Disney's D23 EXPO 2015|url = http://www.marketwatch.com/story/tradition-meets-innovation-at-disney-consumer-products-showcase-at-disneys-d23-expo-2015-2015-06-18|accessdate = 2015-09-22|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150923061902/http://www.marketwatch.com/story/tradition-meets-innovation-at-disney-consumer-products-showcase-at-disneys-d23-expo-2015-2015-06-18|archivedate = September 23, 2015|df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nDisney Consumer Products and Interactive Media launched the Princess Comics line, which was started with Princess Comics graphic novels by Joe Book, in August 2018 at [[Target Corporation|Target]] with Hasbro figures and Hybrid Promotions apparel. This expansion featured Belle, Jasmine, Ariel, Rapunzel and Pocahontas.\n<ref name=icv>{{cite news |last1=Bunge |first1=Nicole |title=Target Gets Exclusive 'Disney Princess Comics' Collections |url=https://icv2.com/articles/news/view/41108/target-gets-exclusive-disney-princess-comics-collections |accessdate=December 13, 2018 |work=ICv2.com |date=August 10, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Disney Princesses==\n<!-- Note: ONLY the princesses CURRENTLY pictured on the Disney Princess website's homepage belong in this section; that is a longstanding convention for this article which predates Disney's first coronation ceremony (for Rapunzel in 2011). Do NOT add any other Disney heroines (such as Alice, Anna, Elsa, Elena or Vanellope) UNTIL they have an official Disney coronation and/or are placed on the homepage as a Disney Princess. It is not known if Alice, Anna, Elsa, Elena or Vanellope will be declared an official Disney Princess (Merida and Rapunzel were both added within a year of the release of their films while Moana was added three years after her film was released). -->\nPrincesses were given an official number in the franchise lineup starting with Snow White as the first and original Disney princess, with Cinderella being the second, followed by Aurora and so on.<ref name=cbs>{{cite news|title=What you don't know about Disney princesses: Roll call|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/what-you-dont-know-about-disney-princesses/4/|accessdate=August 14, 2016|work=CBS News|page=4|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821235416/http://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/what-you-dont-know-about-disney-princesses/4/|archivedate=August 21, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n#[[Snow White (Disney character)|Snow White]] (''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]'')\n#[[Cinderella (Disney character)|Cinderella]] (''[[Cinderella (1950 film)|Cinderella]]'')\n#[[Aurora (Disney)|Aurora]] (''[[Sleeping Beauty (1959 film)|Sleeping Beauty]]'')\n#[[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]] (''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'')\n#[[Belle (Beauty and the Beast)|Belle]] (''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'')\n#[[Jasmine (Disney character)|Jasmine]] (''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]'')\n#[[Pocahontas (character)|Pocahontas]] (''[[Pocahontas (1995 film)|Pocahontas]]'')\n#[[Mulan (Disney character)|Mulan]] (''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]'')\n#[[Tiana (Disney)|Tiana]] (''[[The Princess and the Frog]]'')\n#[[Rapunzel (Tangled)|Rapunzel]] (''[[Tangled]]'')\n#[[Merida (Brave)|Merida]] (''[[Brave (2012 film)|Brave]]'')\n#[[Moana (Disney character)|Moana]] (''[[Moana (2016 film)|Moana]]'')<ref name=\"atmag\"/>\n\n==Meet-and-greets and live events==\n====Disneyland====\n[[File:Disneyland 2012-02-14 Princess and Princesses a.jpg|350px|thumb|right|From left to right: [[Snow White (Disney character)|Snow White]], The Prince; [[Ariel (The Little Mermaid)|Ariel]], [[List of Disney's The Little Mermaid characters#Prince Eric|Prince Eric]]; [[Tiana (Disney)|Tiana]], Prince Naveen; [[Rapunzel (Tangled)|Rapunzel]], [[Flynn Rider]]; [[Cinderella (Disney character)|Cinderella]], [[List of Disney's Cinderella characters#Prince Charming|Prince Charming]]; [[List of Disney's Sleeping Beauty characters#Prince Phillip|Prince Phillip]], [[Aurora (Disney)|Aurora]]; [[Aladdin (Disney character)|Aladdin]], [[Princess Jasmine|Jasmine]]; [[Belle (Beauty and the Beast)|Belle]], [[Beast (Disney)|the Beast]] (before returning to his human form) on February 14th, 2012.]]\nCurrently, all the princesses are available for meet-and-greets in [[Disneyland Resort]] in California. Additionally, In 2006, as part of the \"Year of Million Dreams\" celebration, the [[Fantasyland Theatre|Fantasyland Theater]] began hosting the ''Disneyland Princess Fantasy Faire,'' a show featuring Lords and Ladies that taught young boys and girls the proper etiquette to be a Prince or Princess and featured appearances from the Disney Princesses. In 2010, Rapunzel was given a ''Tangled'' meet-and-greet location. The Carnation Plaza Gardens bandstand, adjacent to Sleeping Beauty Castle, was closed to be replaced by a new Fantasy Faire area in the Spring of 2013.<ref name=lat>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/aug/23/news/la-trb-fantasy-faire-disneyland-princess-0820112 |title=Disneyland princesses moving into new Fantasy Faire village in 2013 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=2011-08-23 |accessdate=2013-03-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301221019/http://articles.latimes.com/2011/aug/23/news/la-trb-fantasy-faire-disneyland-princess-0820112 |archivedate=March 1, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n=====Fantasy Faire=====\n{{Infobox attraction\n<!--GLOBAL STATISTICS-->\n| name                = Fantasy Faire\n| logo                = <!--Use ONLY the filename, not a full [[Image:]] link-->\n| logo_width          = <!--Default is 250px-->\n| image               = <!--Use ONLY the filename, not a full [[Image:]] link-->\n| imagedimensions     = <!--Default is 250px-->\n| caption             = \n<!--INDIVIDUAL PARK STATISTICS-->\n| location            = Disneyland\n| altname             = \n| section             = [[Fantasyland]]\n| coordinates         = <!--Use {{Coord|display=inline}}-->\n| status              = operating\n| cost                = \n| soft_opened         = 