on (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Aion (disambiguation)]]\n* [[D'Eon]], a surname\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "name_user": "109.79.140.200", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Defining are eon)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eon"}
{"title_page": "Tough Guys Don't Dance (novel)", "text_new": "{{infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = Tough Guys Don't Dance\n| image         = Tough Guys Don't Dance (novel).jpg\n| caption       = \n| author        = [[Norman Mailer]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| genre         = \n| publisher     = [[Random House]]\n| pub_date      = 1984\n| english_pub_date =\n| media_type    = Print (hardcover and paperback)\n| pages         = 231\n| isbn          = 0718124545\n| preceded_by   = [[Ancient Evenings]]\n| followed_by   = [[Harlot's Ghost]]\n}}\n'''''Tough Guys Don't Dance''''' (1984) is a [[Noir fiction|noir]] thriller and murder mystery novel by American writer, [[Norman Mailer]],<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/tough-guys-dont-dance/oclc/10483705 Tough Guys Don't Dance], OCLC WorldCat. Retrieved: 2014-05-20.</ref> reminiscent of the works of [[Dashiell Hammett]], [[Mickey Spillane]], and [[Raymond Chandler]]. The novel was written in only two months in order to fulfill a contractual obligation. The [[Tough Guys Don't Dance (film)|book was adapted into a film, directed by Mailer, in 1987]].\n\n== Plot ==\nSet in [[Provincetown]] on [[Cape Cod]] in Massachusetts, the protagonist is Tim Madden, a former bartender and drug runner, currently struggling to make a living as a writer. After waking one morning with a hangover 24 days after his wife has left him, Madden discovers that he has a new tattoo, the passenger seat of his car is covered in blood, and he has no memory of the previous night. Following a tip from the Acting Chief of Police, Madden travels to his marijuana patch to check on its status and finds, to his surprise, the head of an attractive blonde woman has been deposited in a burrow in the exact place he stashes his cannabis harvest.\n\nWith all the evidence for the murder pointing towards him, Madden elects to solve the mystery himself, which brings him into contact with one shady character after another, including corrupt police, criminals, and washed-up boxers. Even a dodgy medium enters the fray as the weary Madden staggers through a succession of dangerous and unforeseen situations.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lehmann |first=Christopher |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/07/25/books/books-of-the-times-086609.html |title=Books Of The Times |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=1984-07-25 |accessdate=2014-05-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Norman Mailer |url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12469.Tough_Guys_Don_t_Dance |title=Tough Guys Don't Dance by Norman Mailer \u2014 Reviews, Discussion, Bookclubs, Lists |publisher=Goodreads.com |date= |accessdate=2014-05-20}}</ref>\n\n== Themes ==\n\n==== Sexuality ====\nSimilar to many of Norman Mailer's writings, ''Tough Guys Don't Dance'' contains themes of sexuality throughout. There are explicit homophobic and misogynistic slurs, descriptive details of male and female genitalia, and an overarching exploration of nearly every character's sexual interests and escapades. \n\n==== Detective Traditions ====\nWriter Tim Madden, in a hazy fog of remembrance, sets out to piece together what happened to him the night before. On his journey, Madden discovers more death, untrustworthy characters, and a heavy dependence on coincidences that are too convenient to simply be coincidences.\n\n==== Masculinity ====\nAs seen in this novel, and also present in Mailer's ''The Time of Her Time'', among others, is a major emphasis on masculinity. Mailer's works are notorious for defining masculinity in a myriad of ways. In this book, violence and homosexuality are two major challenges to the protagonist's masculine image, \"with two gay suicides, oral/anal graphics, and Madden's confession to his macho Irish father. (\"You think I feel like a man most of the time? I don't.\").\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/norman-mailer/tough-guys-dont-dance/|title=TOUGH GUYS DON'T DANCE {{!}} Kirkus Reviews|language=en}}</ref> Also, the title of the book appears about halfway through a story, with a flashback from Tim Madden's days a child learning how to box when his dad told him that \"tough guys don't dance,\" and Madden spends the rest of his life figuring out how not to dance to prove his masculinity, until it is challenged to its very core in the book.\n\n== Literary Criticisms ==\n''Tough Guys Don't Dance'' received mixed reviews upon release. Of his positive reviews, coming from ''The Wall Street Journal'' and the ''St. Petersburg Times'', Christopher Ricks, writing for the ''London Review of Books'', states that \"Mailer can still write like an angel, fallen and flaming.\" He also says, \"Mailer is a master of small surprises...his style is largely to be trusted.\" Ricks does, however, acknowledge the deprecation of Mailer's writings by many American reviewers, signaling a universal understanding of the novel's mixed opinions. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lrb.co.uk/the-paper/v06/n19/christopher-ricks/rectum|title=Christopher Ricks \u00b7 Rectum \u00b7 LRB 18 October 1984|last=Ricks|first=Christopher|date=1984-10-18|website=London Review of Books|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'', among others such as the ''Boston Globe'', published a number of negative reviews.  Denis Donoghue writes, \"But what I mostly feel, reading ''Tough Guys Don't Dance'', is the wretched inadequacy of the novel to the intention it clearly enough avows.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://movies2.nytimes.com/books/98/05/10/specials/mailer-tough.html|title=NYTimes|website=movies2.nytimes.com|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> Additionally, Christopher Lehmann-Haupt, in his segment \"The Books of the Times\" writes, \"On top of the faults I've already hinted at - its implausibility and strutting out of too familiar stratagems and obsessions - one could knock it for being rushed, repetitious, all too nearly an unintended parody of itself.\" <ref>{{Cite news|last=Lehmann-Haupt|first=Christopher|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/07/25/books/books-of-the-times-086609.html|title=Books of the Times|date=1984-07-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nToday, Mailer's novel sports a 3.5 out of 5 score on ''Goodreads'' and receives a fairly negative review on ''Kirkus'', having called it a \"thin, disappointing potpourri overall\u2014seemingly made up as it goes along, with about equal portions of inspiration and self-indulgence.\" The review continues on to say that it is purely Norman Mailer, oftentimes splitting readers between supporters and critics with little room left in the middle. <br />\n==Film adaptation==\nMailer adapted his novel into a movie in 1987, and also acted as director. The [[Tough Guys Don't Dance (film)|resulting film]], starring [[Ryan O'Neal]] and [[Isabella Rossellini]], was not a critical or commercial success.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0094169/ Tough Guys Don't Dance(1987)] Internet Movie Database. Retrieved: 2014-05-20.</ref> The movie currently maintains a 38% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] and a 5.0 on [[IMDb]]. Vincent Canby of the [[The New York Times|New York Times]] wrote, ''Tough Guys Don't Dance'' is not the high point of the Mailer career, but it's a small, entertaining part of it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/18/movies/film-norman-mailer-s-tough-guys-don-t-dance.html|title=Film: Norman Mailer's Tough Guys Don't Dance|last=Canby|first=Vincent|date=1987|website=New York Times|url-status=live|access-date=4/11/20}}</ref> Additionally, Hal Hinson of the Washington Post wrote, \"'Tough Guys' never finds its footing, though, or a workable, consistent style. The movie has its pleasures; I laughed at a lot it, but I've rarely found it harder to determine whether the film's effects were the result of the artist's designs or his ineptitude.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/toughguysdontdancerhinson_a0c934.htm|title='Tough Guys Don't Dance'|last=Hinson|first=Hal|date=1987|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|access-date=4/11/20}}</ref> The movie, however, did have a few supporters in spite of its lackluster showing, yielding less than a fifth of its budget in its box office earnings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.5260/cca.199312|title=Box Office Mojo|last=Vinyard|first=Marc|website=CC Advisor|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Jonathan Rosenbaum of the ''Chicago Reader'', said \"Norman Mailer's best film, adapted from his worst novel, shows a surprising amount of cinematic savvy and style.\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Norman Mailer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tough Guys Don't Dance}}\n[[Category:1984 American novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Norman Mailer]]\n[[Category:American novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:American crime novels]]\n[[Category:American mystery novels]]\n[[Category:Random House books]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = Tough Guys Don't Dance\n| image         = Tough Guys Don't Dance (novel).jpg\n| caption       = \n| author        = [[Norman Mailer]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| genre         = \n| publisher     = [[Random House]]\n| pub_date      = 1984\n| english_pub_date =\n| media_type    = Print (hardcover and paperback)\n| pages         = 231\n| isbn          = 0718124545\n| preceded_by   = [[Ancient Evenings]]\n| followed_by   = [[Harlot's Ghost]]\n}}\n'''''Tough Guys Don't Dance''''' (1984) is a [[Noir fiction|noir]] thriller and murder mystery novel by American writer, [[Norman Mailer]],<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/tough-guys-dont-dance/oclc/10483705 Tough Guys Don't Dance], OCLC WorldCat. Retrieved: 2014-05-20.</ref> reminiscent of the works of [[Dashiell Hammett]], [[Mickey Spillane]], and [[Raymond Chandler]]. The novel was written in only two months in order to fulfill a contractual obligation. The [[Tough Guys Don't Dance (film)|book was adapted into a film, directed by Mailer, in 1987]].\n\n== Plot ==\nSet in [[Provincetown]] on [[Cape Cod]] in Massachusetts, the protagonist is Tim Madden, a former bartender and drug runner, currently struggling to make a living as a writer. After waking one morning with a hangover 24 days after his wife has left him, Madden discovers that he has a new tattoo, the passenger seat of his car is covered in blood, and he has no memory of the previous night. Following a tip from the Acting Chief of Police, Madden travels to his marijuana patch to check on its status and finds, to his surprise, the head of an attractive blonde woman has been deposited in a burrow in the exact place he stashes his cannabis harvest.\n\nWith all the evidence for the murder pointing towards him, Madden elects to solve the mystery himself, which brings him into contact with one shady character after another, including corrupt police, criminals, and washed-up boxers. Even a dodgy medium enters the fray as the weary Madden staggers through a succession of dangerous and unforeseen situations.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lehmann |first=Christopher |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/07/25/books/books-of-the-times-086609.html |title=Books Of The Times |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=1984-07-25 |accessdate=2014-05-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Norman Mailer |url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12469.Tough_Guys_Don_t_Dance |title=Tough Guys Don't Dance by Norman Mailer \u2014 Reviews, Discussion, Bookclubs, Lists |publisher=Goodreads.com |date= |accessdate=2014-05-20}}</ref>\n\n== Themes ==\n\n==== Sexuality ====\nSimilar to many of Norman Mailer's writings, ''Tough Guys Don't Dance'' contains themes of sexuality throughout. There are explicit homophobic and misogynistic slurs, descriptive details of male and female genitalia, and an overarching exploration of nearly every character's sexual interests and escapades. \n\n==== Detective Traditions ====\nWriter Tim Madden, in a hazy fog of remembrance, sets out to piece together what happened to him the night before. On his journey, Madden discovers more death, untrustworthy characters, and a heavy dependence on coincidences that are too convenient to simply be coincidences.\n\n==== Masculinity ====\nAs seen in this novel, and also present in Mailer's ''The Time of Her Time'', among others, is a major emphasis on masculinity. Mailer's works are notorious for defining masculinity in a myriad of ways. In this book, violence and homosexuality are two major challenges to the protagonist's masculine image, \"with two gay suicides, oral/anal graphics, and Madden's confession to his macho Irish father. (\"You think I feel like a man most of the time? I don't.\").\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/norman-mailer/tough-guys-dont-dance/|title=TOUGH GUYS DON'T DANCE {{!}} Kirkus Reviews|language=en}}</ref> Also, the title of the book appears about halfway through a story, with a flashback from Tim Madden's days a child learning how to box when his dad told him that \"tough guys don't dance,\" and Madden spends the rest of his life figuring out how not to dance to prove his masculinity, until it is challenged to its very core in the book.\n\n== Literary Criticisms ==\n''Tough Guys Don't Dance'' received mixed reviews upon release. Of his positive reviews, coming from ''The Wall Street Journal'' and the ''St. Petersburg Times'', Christopher Ricks, writing for the ''London Review of Books'', states that \"Mailer can still write like an angel, fallen and flaming.\" He also says, \"Mailer is a master of small surprises...his style is largely to be trusted.\" Ricks does, however, acknowledge the deprecation of Mailer's writings by many American reviewers, signaling a universal understanding of the novel's mixed opinions. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lrb.co.uk/the-paper/v06/n19/christopher-ricks/rectum|title=Christopher Ricks \u00b7 Rectum \u00b7 LRB 18 October 1984|last=Ricks|first=Christopher|date=1984-10-18|website=London Review of Books|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'', among others such as the ''Boston Globe'', published a number of negative reviews.  Denis Donoghue writes, \"But what I mostly feel, reading ''Tough Guys Don't Dance'', is the wretched inadequacy of the novel to the intention it clearly enough avows.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://movies2.nytimes.com/books/98/05/10/specials/mailer-tough.html|title=NYTimes|website=movies2.nytimes.com|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> Additionally, Christopher Lehmann-Haupt, in his segment \"The Books of the Times\" writes, \"On top of the faults I've already hinted at - its implausibility and strutting out of too familiar stratagems and obsessions - one could knock it for being rushed, repetitious, all too nearly an unintended parody of itself.\" <ref>{{Cite news|last=Lehmann-Haupt|first=Christopher|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/07/25/books/books-of-the-times-086609.html|title=Books of the Times|date=1984-07-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nToday, Mailer's novel sports a 3.5 out of 5 score on ''Goodreads'' and receives a fairly negative review by ''Kirkus'', writing \"thin, disappointing potpourri overall\u2014seemingly made up as it goes along, with about equal portions of inspiration and self-indulgence.\" The review continues on to say that it is purely Norman Mailer, oftentimes splitting readers between supporters and critics with little room left in the middle. <br />\n==Film adaptation==\nMailer adapted his novel into a movie in 1987, and also acted as director. The [[Tough Guys Don't Dance (film)|resulting film]], starring [[Ryan O'Neal]] and [[Isabella Rossellini]], was not a critical or commercial success.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0094169/ Tough Guys Don't Dance(1987)] Internet Movie Database. Retrieved: 2014-05-20.</ref> The movie currently maintains a 38% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] and a 5.0 on [[IMDb]]. Vincent Canby of the [[The New York Times|New York Times]] wrote, ''Tough Guys Don't Dance'' is not the high point of the Mailer career, but it's a small, entertaining part of it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/18/movies/film-norman-mailer-s-tough-guys-don-t-dance.html|title=Film: Norman Mailer's Tough Guys Don't Dance|last=Canby|first=Vincent|date=1987|website=New York Times|url-status=live|access-date=4/11/20}}</ref> Additionally, Hal Hinson of the Washington Post wrote, \"'Tough Guys' never finds its footing, though, or a workable, consistent style. The movie has its pleasures; I laughed at a lot it, but I've rarely found it harder to determine whether the film's effects were the result of the artist's designs or his ineptitude.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/toughguysdontdancerhinson_a0c934.htm|title='Tough Guys Don't Dance'|last=Hinson|first=Hal|date=1987|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|access-date=4/11/20}}</ref> The movie, however, did have a few supporters in spite of its lackluster showing, yielding less than a fifth of its budget in its box office earnings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.5260/cca.199312|title=Box Office Mojo|last=Vinyard|first=Marc|website=CC Advisor|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Jonathan Rosenbaum of the ''Chicago Reader'', said \"Norman Mailer's best film, adapted from his worst novel, shows a surprising amount of cinematic savvy and style.\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Norman Mailer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tough Guys Don't Dance}}\n[[Category:1984 American novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Norman Mailer]]\n[[Category:American novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:American crime novels]]\n[[Category:American mystery novels]]\n[[Category:Random House books]]\n", "name_user": "Zachary.hamstra10", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLiterary Criticisms:touching up the grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tough_Guys_Don%27t_Dance_(novel)"}
